\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Kempsville Volunteer Rescue Squad (KVRS) is an Emergency Medical Services
 (EMS) agency serving the City Of Virginia Beach, Virginia.
 We are a public charity (501.C.3).
 We maintain a large all-volunteer force of Emergency Medical Technicians
 (basic and advanced levels) and Paramedics, and a fleet of mobile intensive
 care ambulances.
 KVRS responds to 9-1-1 and other calls involving illnesses and injuries
 of all natures and magnitudes.
 We are on call 24 hours per day, every day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
KVRS often staffs its ambulances with three-person crews: Driver, Attendant-In-C
harge, and Trainee.
 It is critical that the entire crew communicate well during the response-to-sce
ne phase of each call.
 However, we have identified that crew communications during this phase
 are hampered by pervasive noises (drivetrain, road, interior climate control,
 siren, air horn, etc) as well as by the physical layout of our ambulances,
 which impose substantial distance and obstructions between the crew members
 in the cab and the crew member in the payload module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, KVRS is investigating the feasibility of field testing a headset
 communication system, initially in one ambulance, to determine whether
 it is worthy of inclusion into our standard ambulance design going forward.
\end_layout

